<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Helvetica, sans-serif">
If the answering machine worked like a friends list, (Allowing only those on the list to leave messages.) then it would not take up that much server space. The space allotted could be restricted to a small amount like 100K for all saved messages. That would give you about 20 to 40 saved messages depending on the length allowed for each message. After all, the messages would be only text, and text is not memory intensive. I think this is a workable idea.  It is also very easy to implement in the code.<BR> The messages could even be downloaded while entering the game, and written to a text file on the players PC negating the need to store the messages on the game server after a person has logged on.<BR>Then a simple save command in-game could rewrite any messages that the player wanted to save to a SWG Email log file.<p>[ December 09, 2001: Message edited by: Carith ]<P>--------------------<P>Carith<BR>Soon to be....<BR>Imperial Lackey
</FONT>
